    "description": "<p>This type of robe was worn by chiefs, dignitaries, emirs, and other high-ranking men in 19th-century West Africa. It marked the wearer\u2019s standing and prestige, and also identified him as a Muslim. The talismanic motifs were typically designed and stitched by Qur\u2019anic scholars who found inspiration in Arabic texts. Soninke women no longer practice these embroidery styles and indigo-dyeing techniques, which impacted the weaving traditions of a vast region north and south of the Sahara.</p>\n",
